'''Fabian Rieder''' (born 16 February 2002) is a Swiss professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] for German {{German football updater|Augsburg}} club [[FC Augsburg]] and the [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland national team]].

==Club career==
Born in [[Koppigen]], Rieder is a youth product of the academy of [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]].<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dominic|last=Wuillemin|title=Wie YB eines der grössten Schweizer Talente in den Schoss fällt|url=https://www.bernerzeitung.ch/wie-yb-eines-der-groessten-schweizer-talente-in-den-schoss-faellt-124520264195|newspaper=[[Berner Zeitung]]|date=30 July 2022|access-date=5 June 2025|language=de}}</ref> He made his professional debut with Young Boys in a goalless [[Swiss Super League]] tie with [[Servette FC|Servette]] on 17 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Servette vs. Young Boys|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2020/10/17/switzerland/super-league/servette-fc-geneve/bsc-young-boys-bern/3361620/|website=Soccerway|date=17 October 2020|access-date=5 June 2025}}</ref> He made his first Continental appearance with Young Boys in a 2–1 defeat against [[AS Roma|Roma]] in the [[Europa League]] on 22 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Young Boys Bern vs. AS Roma|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/match/_/gameId/585996|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=22 October 2020|access-date=5 June 2025}}</ref> Rieder played in all six of Young Boys [[UEFA Champions League]] [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League#Group F|group stage]] matches in the 2021–22 season, scoring his first continental goal in a 1–1 tie against [[Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{Cite web|first=Michael|last=Benson|title=Mason Greenwood scores beautiful acrobatic goal, but much-changed Manchester United are held to draw by Young Boys in final Champions League group.|url=https://talksport.com/football/998817/mason-greenwood-goal-manchester-united-young-boys-champions-league/|website=[[Talksport]]|date=8 December 2021|access-date=5 June 2025}}</ref>

On 31 August 2023, Rieder joined French side [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] for a reported fee of €15 million (including add-ons),<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Mercato. Le milieu de terrain suisse Fabian Rieder signe au Stade Rennais |url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/football/stade-rennais/officiel-le-milieu-de-terrain-suisse-fabian-rieder-signe-au-stade-rennais-4abc1a38-47d8-11ee-bce2-f20034b4a036|website=[[Ouest-France]]|date=31 August 2023|access-date=2 September 2023|language=fr}}</ref> signing a four-year contract with the club.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=31 August 2023 |title=Fabian Rieder 2027 ! |url=https://www.staderennais.com/fabian-rieder-2027|website=Stade Rennais F.C.|access-date=31 August 2023|language=fr}}</ref> On 24 June 2024, he signed a one-year loan contract with [[Bundesliga]] club [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Rieder joins VfB on loan|url=https://www.vfb.de/en/vfb/latest/news/professionals/2324/vfb-stuttgart-verpflichtet-fabian-rieder-/|website=VfB Stuttgart|date=24 June 2024}}</ref>

On 1 September 2025, Rieder returned to [[Bundesliga]] and signed a five-year contract with [[FC Augsburg]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=FC Augsburg|url=https://www.fcaugsburg.de/en/article/fc-augsburg-sign-switzerland-international-fabian-rieder-22350|title=FC Augsburg sign Switzerland international Fabian Rieder|date=1 September 2025|access-date=4 September 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
Rieder played for all Swiss youth national teams before receiving his first call-up for the [[Switzerland national football team|senior national team]] for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.football.ch/sfv/nationalteams/a-team/news/murat-yakin-gibt-schweizer-wm-aufgebot-bekannt.aspx |title=Murat Yakin gibt Schweizer WM-Aufgebot bekannt |trans-title=Murat Yakin announces Swiss World Cup squad|publisher=[[Swiss Football Association]] |date=9 November 2022 |access-date=9 November 2022 |language=de}}</ref> At said tournament on 25 November, he debuted in a 1–0 victory against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] as a substitute in the 81st minute.<ref>{{Cite web|title=WM-Debütant Rieder: Als ob er immer auf der Seite spielen würde|url=https://www.srf.ch/sport/fussball/fifa-wm-2022/am-tag-nach-dem-kamerun-spiel-wm-debuetant-rieder-als-ob-er-immer-auf-der-seite-spielen-wuerde|publisher=[[Swiss Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=25 November 2022|access-date=5 June 2025|language=de}}</ref> Rieder started in the next match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dan|last=Urner|title=«Es tut weh»: Die Stimmen zur Schweizer Niederlage gegen Brasilien|url=https://www.luzernerzeitung.ch/news-service/sport/fussball-wm-es-tut-weh-die-stimmen-zur-schweizer-niederlage-gegen-brasilien-ld.2379763|newspaper=[[Luzerner Zeitung]]|date=28 November 2022|access-date=5 June 2025|language=de}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Rieder was named in Switzerland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/switzerland-announce-26-man-squad-euro-2024-2024-06-07/|title=Switzerland announce 26-man squad for Euro 2024|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=7 June 2024|access-date=16 June 2024}}</ref> He played the final four minutes of the team's opening match at the tournament, replacing [[Dan Ndoye]] in a 3–1 victory against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in Cologne.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy99107knekt#Line-ups|title=Hungary 1-3 Switzerland Live|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=16 July 2024|access-date=5 June 2025}}</ref>

